Why the cited portions do not make the claim obvious

US 10,459,887 Claim 1 is primarily about predictive application pre-launch. Its trigger is that an icon moves into a specified region around the center of the display. The application is loaded in memory before selection, and after selection the application interface or preview is presented. Claim 1 does not disclose [Applicant to insert missing feature(s)]. 

US 10,459,887 Claim 8 only adds contextual information in a zoomed-in icon view. It does not explain [Applicant to insert missing mechanism(s)]. 

US 2019/0339860 ¶¶ 0231–0233 are about watch-face complications moving among predefined locations. The displayed information changes because the complication moves to a different-sized location. This is still a size/location-based display behavior, not [Applicant to insert claimed technical distinction]. 

Under §103, the Office must provide a clear reason why the claimed invention as a whole would have been obvious, and the cited references must support the missing claim limitations or provide a reason to add them. MPEP §2143 states that the key to a §103 rejection is clear articulation of why the claimed invention would have been obvious, and MPEP §2142 states that the examiner must set forth a prima facie case supported by evidence.

Here, the cited portions do not provide that bridge.


